PROPERTY: Authorizes and directs the Louisiana Law Institute to study the constitutional
authority to expropriate property
1 A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION
2 To authorize and direct the Louisiana State Law Institute to study the Louisiana Supreme
3 Court decision in Plaquemines Port Harbor and Terminal Dist. v. Nguyen, No.
4 2025-C-00827 (La. 3/6/26), and its implications on the expropriation authority
5 provided for in the Constitution of Louisiana and R.S. 19:2.
6 WHEREAS, on March 6, 2026, the Louisiana Supreme Court issued its opinion in
7 Plaquemines Port Harbor and Terminal Dist. v. Nguyen, No. 2025-C-00827 (La. 3/6/26),
8 holding that a public port authority's expropriation of private property for the purpose of
9 leasing that property exclusively for a private company's predominant use is unconstitutional
10 because the taking does not satisfy the "public purpose" requirement of Article I, Section 4
11 of the Constitution of Louisiana; and
12 WHEREAS, the court emphasized that the 2006 amendment to Article I, Section 4
13 strictly limits the definition of "public purpose" for eminent domain and prohibits takings
14 that result in predominant private use or benefit even when a public entity retains nominal
15 ownership; and
16 WHEREAS, in 2009, the legislature enacted Act No. 517, which added R.S. 19:2(12)
17 to grant private corporations and partnerships the power of expropriation under certain
18 circumstances; and
19 WHEREAS, in 2020, the legislature enacted Act No. 61, which further amended the
20 2009 Act by refining definitions, procedures, and the exercise of eminent domain; and
